{
  "doc_id": "49666",
  "text": "McHR1 is a G protein-coupled receptor for the neuropeptide McH. The function of the McH/McHR1 signaling pathway is to mobilize intracellular ca 2+ and reduce forskolin-elevated cAMP levels [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Previous studies revealed that MCH is a functional antagonist of α-melanocyte-stimulating hormone (α-MSH) and could partially inhibit the induction of melanogenesis by α-MSH in human melanocytes [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . MCHR1 expression has been reported in human melanocytes [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Recently, McHR1 has been suggested as a novel antigen with high specificity in vitiligo [CITATION_7] . In addition, four epitope domains (amino acids 51-80, 85-98, 154-158, 254-260) have been identified as the antibody binding sites [CITATION_8] . Also, the equivalent peptide sequence to epitopes 51-80 and 85-98, 154-158 and 254-260 in rat McHR1 are predicted to lie in the extracellular N-terminal domain, the first extracellular loop, and the second extracellular loop of the receptor, respectively [CITATION_9] .",
